observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management take full opportunity to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE balances under COA Circular No. 2020-006 by undertaking the following steps:
1. Ensure the proper conduct of physical count of all PPEs and proper and accurate preparation of the RPCPPE; 
2. Adhere to the prescribed guidelines and forms in preparing the property and accounting records of all PPEs; and
3. Reconcile the RPCPPE with the property and accounting records;
4. Identify and recognize in the books the PPE items found at station;
5. Determine non-existing/missing properties and follow the prescribed procedures for disposition and derecognition; and
6. Determine unserviceable properties and follow the prescribed procedures for disposal and derecognition in the books of accounts.

We reiterated and recommended that Management:
7. Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding cash advances, especially from all AOs and employees still connected with the LGU, pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;
8. Be reminded that an official/employee who is separated from the service caused by reassignment/ transfer/retirement/death, must not be given clearance unless their outstanding cash advances are first settled;
9. Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and avoid granting additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made pursuant to Section 89 of PD No. 1445;
10. Institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted; and
11. File a request to the Commission Audit for authority to write-off and/or adjust the dormant or non-moving accounts as prescribed in COA Circular Nos. 2016-005. The request must be duly supported by the documents required in the said Circular.

15. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit liquidation reports of outstanding fund transfers received from various agencies which purposes were already completed, return any unspent amount and henceforth, strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 4 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
16. Be reminded that if the disposition of the unspent/unutilized amount is not provided in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA), Trust Agreement or Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), the Agency may, at their option, utilize the said amount by sending a letter to the source agency requesting approval to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund pursuant to Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
17. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the Due to NGAs account and take up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries in the books for the fair presentation of the said account in the FS.

20. Submit the lacking documents of the contracts and the corresponding payments and explain the noted deficiencies in some of the submitted documents;
21. Ensure that the validity period of the performance and warranty securities posted by the contractors are in accordance with Sections 62.2.2 and 62.2.3 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
22. Exercise strictest scrutiny in the preparation of bidding documents, conduct of procurement activities in accordance with the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and other relevant procurement guidelines and supporting the transactions with complete documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001.

24. Explain why the additional works and materials for the Construction of Multi-purpose Rooftop at MDRRMO Building was separately procured and why its procurement/implementation was delayed despite the availability of funds;
25. Prepare the required Detailed Engineering of the Contract before prosecuting any infrastructure project in accordance with Section 17.6, Rule VI of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
26. Ensure the use/application of appropriate methods of procurement, in accordance with the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, to cover unavoidable and justifiable increase/decrease in quantities of work including new work items that are not included in the original infrastructure contracts.

29. Direct the LDRRMO to submit the LDRRMFIP showing the allocation of LDRRMF for both current and the unexpended balance of the prior years’ DRRMF;
30. Cause the timely and full implementation of all programmed DRRMF PPAs;
31. Ensure that the transfer of the unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE must be made at the end of the year in accordance with Item 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2021-002; and
32. Refrain from charging against the LDRRMF those expenditures not pertaining to disaster risk reduction and management or not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established, otherwise, these transactions shall be disallowed in audit.

41. Explain for the delays incurred in the implementation of the project;
42. Submit the approved suspension and resume work orders and other relevant documents pertaining to the delays and the proposed extension of contract time, if any;
43. Strengthen its monitoring and supervision of the overall project implementation and formulate measures to address the causes of delay; and
44. Direct the Contractor to exert best efforts to timely implement and complete the PRDP Subproject.

47. Review and evaluate the existing manpower resources to ensure adequate staffing pattern that suit the present needs of the offices and create clear-cut policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring job orders/holders of COS;
48. Maximize the use of existing work force and resort to job order hiring only in the exigency of the service and if it is not feasible for the LGU to hire said services under a casual or contractual appointment;
49. Clearly define in the contract the nature of works or activities to be done by the job orders/holders of COS; and
50. Require the submission of individual and quantified accomplishment reports and definite proof of identification to support the payments and require the Disbursing Officer to personally pay at the premises of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer the daily/monthly wage of the job orders/holders of COs especially those assigned in the field or in the barangays for internal control purposes.

49. Submit the lacking documentary requirements on the subject procurement transactions and explain for the deficiencies noted therein;
50. Comply with the requirements of adequate procurement planning in accordance with Section 7 of RA No. 9184 that will regulate procurement activities; and
51. Strictly abide with the procedural guidelines for the alternative mode of procurement appropriate and applicable in each transaction.

52. Submit plausible explanation/justification on the deficiencies and discrepancies noted in the submitted documents;
53. Strictly adhere to the above cited provisions on the posting of performance security, warranty security and release of retention money to the contractor; and
54. Direct concerned officials to ensure that payments on procurements for infrastructure projects are properly supported with complete documentation.

62. Require the MGSO to prepare and submit to the Accounting Unit on a weekly basis the SSMI as basis for taking up the expense accounts;
63. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct periodic physical count of all supplies and materials on hand, submit the required RPCI and reconcile the same with the accounting records as often as necessary; and
64. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the acquisition and issuance of the supplies and materials inventory based on IPSAS 12, Inventories, and make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of the affected inventory and expense accounts.

We reiterated the following to Management:

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count annually, prepare the RPCPPE by themselves, certify it and have it approved by the LCE, together with the RPCLRN of the LGU;

Instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger (GL) account balances and with the property records;

Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and

Require the Inventory Committee to immediately request authority to dispose of those identified unserviceable and obsolete PPE and drop from the books the book value thereof upon approval in accordance with existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations.

We reiterated and recommended that Management:

Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding cash advances, especially from all AOs and employees still connected with the LGU, pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;

Stop the practice of granting elected officials and national government employees cash advances for purposes other than official traveling expenses and instead designate a special disbursing officer to handle/facilitate payment of various operating expenses;

Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances and avoid granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made pursuant to Section 89 of PD No. 1445; and

Institute appropriate administrative and/or legal action against the AO for the immediate settlement of these cash advances. Otherwise, we will be compelled to exhaust the said legal remedies for violating Article 217 and 218 of the Revised Penal Code and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 which is punishable under Section 128 of the same Code.

