The LGSF COVID-19 FA to LGU must only be used or utilized for allowable COVID-19 PPAs pursuant to DBM LBC No. 128. Unallowable expenditures charged against it must immediately be reverted back to the fund;
The BAC and the Procuring Unit must obtain prevailing market prices of goods ought to be purchased, through price inquiry from other municipalities, suppliers, and online scanning prior to conducting Negotiated Procurement or any other mode of procurement as a tool for obtaining prices most advantageous to the government;
Devise an ideal and effective Plan and Budget and submit periodic Accomplishment Report on the programs, strategies, and efforts relative to the response against COVID-19 as a measuring tool on the LGU’s action of curtailing, mitigating, eliminating the COVID-19 in the municipality in relation to Section 14 of RA No. 11494; and
Satisfactory explanation be obtained from the BAC, Procuring Unit, HOPE and other concerned LGU officers on excessive prices of procured goods for COVID-19 particularly on the procurement of Lungene Antigen Test Kits and Vitamin C for supplements to Senior Citizens.

All developmental projects be implemented immediately as planned for the constituents to enjoy the benefits they may be derived from the projects and ensure that the development projects to be funded out of the 20 per cent DF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready;
The BAC, HOPE, and other concerned LGU fiscal officers must adhere strictly to the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR in the procurement process.  Every detail of the procurement documents must be reviewed as to its correctness, particularly the details of the Approved Budget for the Contract, dates of NOA, Contract, NTP and other vital documents supporting the procurement;
Require contractors to post warranty security for all completed and accepted projects; and
Explanation be submitted on the deficiencies noted particularly on the posting of Performance Security by the successful bidders, dates of contracts signing, receipt of NOA, NTP and others documents.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursements for repairs made by the Municipality are supported with complete and appropriate documentation as prescribed in Section 9.1.3.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 362 Volume I of GAAM;
Direct the MGSO to submit the Pre-repair Evaluation Reports and the Post-inspection Reports relative to the above-mentioned transactions and other homogenous disbursements; and
Require that Certificates of Acceptance and RWMs be prepared by the MGSO and approved by the Local Chief Executive, in case of major repairs and if the repairs need replacement.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that:

The Inventory Team conduct complete physical inventory-taking of all PPE and submit a complete RPCPPE not later than January 31 of each year;

The Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) and Municipal Accountant prioritize reconciliation of the results of the inventory count with the property and accounting records, look into the noted discrepancies and effect/prepare the necessary adjusting entries, as the case may be;

The MGSO must conduct physical inventory and inspection of all unserviceable and obsolete items, prepare and submit the IIRUP and facilitate the immediate disposal of those items so that they may be dropped from the books of accounts; and 

The Municipal Accountant must make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct all erroneous recording/classification of PPE accounts.

We recommended that:

The LGU, through the concerned offices/departments, observe the prudent fund management in its effort to curtail/eliminate/mitigate the spread of COVID-19 in the locality.  Henceforth, all PPAs related to COVID-19 must be judiciously planned according to priorities considering the scarce resources of the LGU and the urgent needs for health, safety, and livelihood of the constituents; 

Observe and adhere to the required posting of APP, NOA, and PPAs implemented by the LGU to the GPPB portal for transparency and reportorial compliance;  

Satisfactory explanation is requested on the observations made in the utilization and disbursement of BGCM Fund, otherwise transactions covered by said observations will be suspended or disallowed in audit as the case maybe; and

The MGSO, Municipal Disaster Risk and Reduction Management Officer (MDRRMO) and other concerned accountable for  all procurement and subsequent distribution of food reliefs, are requested to fully account and submit inventory report on the food reliefs received, distributed and on hand.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing fines and penalties for violators thereof;

Ensure that the composition of the SWMB complies with Section 12 of RA No. 9003;

Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 17 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and

Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) or its equivalent officers/employees to:

Strictly comply with the existing rules and regulations prescribing the guidelines in the formulation of Annual GPB, development of gender issues, GAD activities, and implementation and monitoring of the GPB.  Mainstreaming of regular PPAs must be made through the use of HGDG assessment tools to justify the attribution of the portion or whole costs to GAD budget; 

Avoid the general statements of the gender issue which do not necessarily reflect gender differences in the situation of women and men.  The gender issue must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex disaggregated data and gender analysis results;

Utilize the GAD Fund only for acceptable PPAs that would address the identified gender issues in the locality based on the RA No. 9710 or the  Magna Carta of Women, PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended, and other relevant international commitments; and

Stop the granting of additional benefits to LGU employees without legal basis at the disguise of GAD activity.

We recommended the following:

Implement immediately and on timely basis the identified PPAs under the 20 per cent DF.  The Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer must monitor the implementation of the projects to fast tract its completion;

The members of the Bids and Awards Committee schedule early all procurements activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion; 

All 20 per cent DF projects must be effectively planned and the same must be procurement-and implementation-ready; and

Observe the proper realignment of appropriated budget pursuant to law to avoid legal issue that may hamper the socio-economic of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management require the HRMO to:

Prepare a Summary of Leave Credit Balances of all employees at the end of the year and have the employees attest the remaining balance of their leave credits on their leave cards;

Submit a MRAUA per department on a monthly basis to the Accounting Office, with complete attachments of each employee’s DTR, locator slip, approved leave, travel order and certificate of appearance.

