We recommended that the Municipality, through the Accounting Department, increase efforts in strengthening the controls in the grant, liquidation and monitoring of cash advances by:

Ensuring that no additional cash advances be granted to those officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances;

Strictly enforcing the liquidation of cash advances within the prescribed period by sending demand letters regularly, particularly to accountable officers and employees who are still in active service;

Articulating policies and procedures for the settlement of accountabilities especially to those planning to retire, resign or transfer to other agencies prior to issuance of clearance certificate to them; and

Imposing the withholding of salary and instituting the other sanctions and penal provisions against those erring accountable officers/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor file a request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated cash advances with the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor if settlement/collectability is already remote, following the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of unliquidated cash advances per COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Engineer to strengthen and hasten the full implementation of PPAs programmed in the current year’s 20 per cent Development Plan, as well as those in the Continuing Appropriation particularly those partaking the nature of Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses;

Review unimplemented PPAs in CY 2006 to CY 2017 and ascertain the viability of implementation for the ensuing year, otherwise, reprogram for a more viable and significant PPAs in accordance to the socio-economic development and environmental management requirements; 

Intensify detailed engineering/planning activities so as not to hamper project implementation and formulate PPAs having detailed description, such as specific project name, location,  feasible schedule of project implementation and expected output for timely implementation of the project; and

Maximize the utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and implement the programs, projects and activities within the targeted timeframe to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all.

We recommended that Management:

Comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only the garbage that is properly segregated;

Cause the immediate closure of the LGUs existing open dumpsite and expedite the establishment and completion of the Categorized Waste Final Disposal Facility;

Provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and

Exert more effort on preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under Republic Act No. 9003.

